<h2 id="problem">Problem</h2>

<p>Imagine youâ€™re an early-career designer who wanted to depeen their understanding of typography, what do you do? Plugging â€œhow to get better at typographyâ€ into Google returns a deluge of mediocre â€œcontentâ€ from SaaS company blogs. Eventually, you read enough of these guides to understand the components of type usage: font choice &amp; pairings, size scale, accessibility, etc. Then, you make your queries more specific and find the best guide on each topic.</p>

<p>Thatâ€™s the process of learning anything on the internet. There are several metaskills at work here:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Knowing what to search for</li>
  <li>Decomposing your need into different steps</li>
  <li>Knowing which guide to follow for each step</li>
</ol>

<p>The tricky thing is that most of these skills are catch-22s. How do you know to search for when you donâ€™t know what youâ€™re supposed to learn? How do you decompose a problem into steps when you donâ€™t understand a problem? How do you know what the best guide is for each step when you donâ€™t know how that step works?</p>

<p>As a result, Iâ€™ve lost track of the number of times Iâ€™ve said to myself â€œIâ€™m going to learn how to build a basic CRUD app this weekendâ€ only to lose the entire two days wading through an ocean of guides without writing any code.</p>

<p>For many domains of craft like product design and software engineering (though I canâ€™t speak as well to the latter), thereâ€™s already a ton of great guides out there for most things youâ€™d want to learn<sup id="fnref:1" role="doc-noteref"><a href="#fn:1" class="footnote">1</a></sup>. The real problem is figuring out which ones to follow. If we want to increase the amount of knowledge in the wrold, the marginal unit of expert time is better spent organizing than producing.</p>

<h2 id="existing-solutions">Existing solutions</h2>

<p><em>Khan academy knowledge map</em></p>

<p>One great example of this is Khan Academyâ€™s now defunct knowledge map of Kâ€“12 math. Having an authoritative source map out the knowledge space and their dependencies + provide a good resource to learn it means that a lot of the metawork outlined above is done for learners.</p>

<figure>
  <img class="blogImage" src="/assets/blogImg/curation/knowledgeMap1.png" alt="khan academy knowledge map" />
